Thus, these studies demonstrate that multiple mechanisms work together for the proposed multi-stimuli-response drug delivery system. (1) UiO-n family MOFs are acid-sensitive MOFs that destroy when exposed to low pH because of the protonation of the carboxylic acid units of the linker, resulting in payload release [92]. By utilization of this superior characteristic, we designed a UiO-66 MOF-based pH-responsive drug delivery system. (2) Protonation-induced MOF destruction is one of the intriguing approaches for achieving pH-induced load release. Because of this, we amino-functionalized the UiO-66 MOF, so that the nanocarriers remain deprotonated under physiological pH (~7.4). However, they are susceptible to be protonated (-NH2 turns into –NH3
                        + when the pH is lower than 6.3) when exposed to the acidic environment of the cancerous cells, resulting in structural destruction of the MOF and release of the encapsulated drugs at the acidic tumor site [104]. (3) After drug loading, the pores of the MOF were locked via the formation of the folded aptamer, that usually consists of stems and loops. When exposed to nucleolin stimulus which is overexpressed on MDA-MB-231 cancer cells, the caps are unlocked via the formation of the aptamer-nucleolin complex, leading to the release of the payload. (4) In addition, magnetic-responsive drug delivery systems are often made from magnetic cores and MOF shells. Althought this characteristic has not been fully utilized in this study, we have fabricated a Fe3O4@MOF nanocarrier whose potential application for magnetic stimuli-responsive drug delivery remains open to the scientific community. Thus, we have reported an intelligent multi-stimuli-responsive drug delivery system which possessed “four-in-one” functions, which is of paramount importance from the practical point of view [105]. Compared to other similar drug delivery systems (Table 1
                        ) [66,67,106–112], the fabricated nanocarrier possesses the advantages of high drug loading efficiency, rapid imaging speed, superior targeting ability, controlled drug release, and excellent cytotoxicity, which paves a new way to cancer therapy.
